<TITLE> Swiss right-winger Blocher loses cabinet seat </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ZURICH, Dec 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Swiss parliament ousted right-wing politician and Justice Minister Christoph Blocher from Switzerland's coalition government on Wednesday in a surprise move after a controversial election in October. Billionaire industrialist Blocher -- prominent in the People's Party (SVP) parliamentary election campaign which the UN and rights groups branded racist -- failed in his bid for re-election to the seven-member, cross-party Federal Council. SVP politician Eveline Widmer-Schlumpf, from the eastern Swiss canton (state) of Grisons, was proposed as a candidate for Blocher's cabinet seat by rival parties. "If Blocher is not elected then the SVP will go into opposition," said outgoing SVP party president Ueli Maurer. If the SVP, the largest party in Switzerland's parliament, adopts an antagonistic stance, it could throw a decades-old system of power-sharing into disarray. It was not immediately clear if Widmer-Schlumpf would accept the cabinet se
